<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,1813,1999]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,279,1813,1839]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is distinguished from 
<taxonomicName box="[699,1000,1813,1838]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Leptotyphlops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="boulengeri">
<emphasis box="[699,1000,1813,1838]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Leptotyphlops boulengeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its high middorsal and subcaudal counts and from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wallach" authorityYear="1996" box="[354,476,1853,1878]" class="Reptilia" family="Leptotyphlopidae" genus="Leptotyphlops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="drewesi">
<emphasis box="[354,476,1853,1878]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">L. drewesi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its broad rostral shield and reticulate colour pattern. Skull robust, with fused parietal bones (
<figureCitation box="[329,414,1893,1919]" captionStart="PLATE 4" captionStartId="11.[151,238,1626,1650]" captionTargetBox="[307,1289,197,1614]" captionTargetId="figure-257@11.[263,1331,162,1634]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="PLATE 4. Figure 1. Dorsal views of the skulls of Leptotyphlops. A. Leptotyphlops nigricans (MCZ 21473) and B. Leptotyphlops kafubi (FMNH 56374), both after List (1966). KEY to bone abbreviations from List, 1966: Ax = axis, At = atlas, Eo = exoccipital, F = frontal, M = maxilla, N = nasal, P = parietal, Pf = prefrontal, Po = prootic, So = supraoccipital. C. Leptotyphlops cairi, after Abdeen et al. (1991). KEY to bone abbreviations from Abdeen et al., 1991: B.OC. = basioccipital; B.SP. = basisphenoid; C.T.C. = cartilaginouis trebacula cranii; EX.OC. = exoccipital; FR. = frontal; L.P.P.MX. = lateral process of maxilla; MX. = maxilla; NA. = nasal; OC.CO. = occipital condyle; P.MX. = premaxilla; P.OT. = prootic; P.VO. = prevomer; PA. = palatine; PR. = parietal; PR.FR. = prefrontal; PR.L.DG. = lateral downgrowth of parietal; PT. = pterygoid; S.OC. = supraoccipital. The lines represent 1 mm to scale. The stipple indicates thin transparent membrane. Figure 2. Dorsal views of the skulls of Leptotyphlops. A. Leptotyphlops nigroterminus sp. nov. (ZMB 51610); B. Leptotyphlops macrurus (BMNH 1957.1.10.26); C. Leptotyphlops boulengeri (MCZ 40087); D. Leptotyphlops reticulatus (BMNH 1954.1.12.77). E. Leptotyphlops longicaudus (NMZB-UM 29371); F. Leptotyphlops blanfordii (BMNH 1977.833); G. Leptotyphlops nursii (FMNH 66158). H. Leptotyphlops scutifrons merkeri (NMZB 8089). The lines represent 1 mm to scale. KEY: f = frontal; n = nasal; p = parietal; pp = postparietal; so = supraoccipital." pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Plate 4</figureCitation>
, Fig 2D).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="18" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,1813,1999]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,350,1933,1959]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Description.</emphasis>
Body cylindrical, with head broadened, flattened and distinct from neck, the moderate tail tapers to a small conical terminal spine.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,152,858]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Snout rounded, rostral moderate (0.35 head width), wider than nasals anteriorly, barely reaching level of eyes posteriorly, a deep preoral groove present ventrally but rostral not beaked or extending below lip line in lateral view. Behind rostral, upper lip bordered by an infranasal (nostril midway between rostral and supralabial along nasal suture), moderate anterior supralabial subequal in size to infranasal with width along lip equal to that of infranasal, large ocular with eye near upper anterior edge, and moderate posterior supralabial. Supraoculars twice as long as wide, anteriorly wedged between supranasal and ocular, posteriorly wedged between a large hexagonal frontal and a small postfrontal, which is followed by a larger and wider interparietal and a long but narrow interoccipital, the next middorsal scale is as wide as the interparietal. Parietals transverse, subequal to the enlarged occipitals, in contact with the moderate posterior supralabials. Temporal single. No mental.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,152,858]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Body covered with 14 rows of smooth, imbricate, subequal scales. Reduction to 10 rows on tail takes place lateral to the crescent-shaped cloacal shield. Total middorsals 227–238; subcaudals 29–32.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,152,858]" box="[198,963,632,658]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Total length/tail ratio 9.2–12.5; total length/diameter ratio 41–57.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,152,858]" box="[198,1410,672,698]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Three to seven middorsal scale rows dark to light brown, each scale bordered with white, venter cream.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,152,858]" box="[198,1368,711,738]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,256,711,737]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Size.</emphasis>
Largest specimen (BMNH 1954.1.12.77 — Hargeisha, 
<collectingCountry box="[912,1009,712,738]" name="Somalia" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Somalia</collectingCountry>
) has a total length of 
<quantity box="[1263,1363,712,738]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.01" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" unit="mm" value="201.0">201 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
